Note: When participant tried on standard size glasses, she felt that they were immediately pressing on the sides of her head behind her ears. Switched to glasses #2, size large, immediately before starting session.
Participant starts session on grey couch but walks around to take pictures and images.
Participant states that a few of the times she’s tried to take a photo Meta responds with “ok cancel”. Wonders if it’s because she is moving around too much.
Participant notes no issues with taking and sending videos.
Participant states she told Meta to take a video but forgot to say “to send to moderator” and Meta prompted her after taking the video by asking who she wanted to send it to.
Participant states the experience of taking images and videos on the older glasses is fine except that you can’t see what they look like before sending.
Participant has moved to light green chair.
Participant has asked Meta multiple times about the average apartment cost in places outside of Arizona, but Meta seems to keep defaulting to Tempe, AZ.

Participant is finding that she can communicate back and forth with the device about the same topic rather than saying “hey meta” every time. Participant states the answers Meta gave to her questions about hiking ideas in different states were “basic”. Expected more options but states she could see why it might not want to give a long list. She did prompt Meta for more options after it only gave her three.
Participant states the communication was not bad when asking about a summary of a book.
Participant feels like before she was asking basic questions, using the prompt question list, today she wanted to ask more questions specific to things she wanted to know about.
Participant switched to dark green chair.
Participant began to play music on Spotify. Had to prompt a few separate times to get Meta to lower volume using the command “Hey Meta, lower volume”.

Participant attempted to message moderator on WhatsApp and at first, Meta said “ok cancel”. Upon second try, Meta did open and send message in WhatsApp. Participant notes Meta stopped music automatically when she began to send message and re-started he music automatically after the message was sent.
Participant states there is no difference in comfort or audio experience between these glasses and Gen III glasses.
Participant states when she received a message, Meta gave her the option to suspend messages for an hour.
Participant asked Meta to play popular music on Spotify. States she was expecting Meta to play popular music from different genres but it is playing different songs from the same genre.

Participant asked Meta to play message from moderator (using moderator’s name), Meta said “It can’t filter from contacts”. So moderator then asked “what is the last message”, after which Meta was able to play last message. Participant wonders why it couldn’t just play the most recent message the first time she asked.

Participant was unable to send reply to moderator in WhatsApp. Meta delivered error message stating “error has occurred” and then asks participant to open WhatsApp again. Participant also notes it plays a ringtone. Spotify continued to play.
Participant instructed Spotify to go to the next song, and Meta responded by asking if she wanted to send message. Participant said yes and Meta sent message without issue.

Participant states Meta said that she received a long message from moderator. Participant asked Meta to read the message but Meta would not read the message. Participant read message on the phone and responded using verbal commands on the device.

Participant asked Meta to change the song on Spotify and missed incoming message from moderator. When participant asked Meta to read the message, Meta said it was unable to because it had been more than a minute.
Participant is somewhat impressed by Meta’s ability to pick up dictation. States Meta works better than any of the voice to text software on her phone.
Participant moved to grey couch.
Participant wishes that Meta would say something after she tells it to stop music on Spotify instead of abruptly stopping the music without including any verbal input.

Participant said “hey Meta” then paused because she wasn’t sure what to ask. When she paused, Meta inserted an advertisement about the glasses. She remembers that it said something about “Meta Oakley glasses”.

Participant asked Meta for directions to an address on Central Avenue. Meta gave directions but participant notes directions don’t make sense for current starting location. Participant asked Meta to repeat the directions and Meta gave same directions.
Participant states Meta must think we are somewhere closer to central Phoenix based on the directions it gave.

Participant asked for directions to a specific location. Meta sent directions to phone and also mentioned something about participant being able to listen to directions, although participant is not sure exactly what it said.
Participant moved to light green chair.
